This represents a diamond (rotated square) centered at (1, 1) with vertices at (2, 1), (1, 2), (0, 1), and (1, 0). The area of this diamond in the first quadrant is calculated as follows: 1. The area of a diamond (rotated square) with diagonals of length 2 (from (0, 1) to (2, 1) and from (1, 0) to (1, 2)) is \( \frac{2 \times 2}{2} = 2 \). Since the region is symmetric across both axes, each quadrant will have an area of 2. Therefore, the total area is \( 4 \times 2 = 8 \). To verify, we consider the transformation to the \( uv \)-plane where \( u = |x| \) and \( v = |y| \). The inequality becomes \( |u - 1| + |v - 1| \le 1 \), which is a diamond centered at (1, 1) with vertices at (2, 1), (1, 2), (0, 1), and (1, 0). The area in the \( uv \)-plane is 2, and mapping back to the \( xy \)-plane (each point (u, v) corresponds to four points in the xy-plane) results in an area of \( 4 \times 2 = 8 \). Thus, the area of the region defined by \( ||x| - 1| + ||y| - 1| \le 1 \) is \(\boxed{8}\).
